            "answer_text": "You can achieve this by putting the text in a parent element like a div which has an id or a class.After doing that you can simply use css rules to rotate the element you use it alongside javascript to make it more practical and dynamic. Short Example <div id=\u201dmytext\u201d>Hello</div> <style> #mytext { transform:rotate(90deg); webkit-transform:rotate(90deg); /*You should handle several browsers*/  }  </style>  <script> //Assumming you have jquery you can dynamically rotate the text in this manner when an event happens $(document).on(\u201c#event\u201d, \u201c#element\u201d, function(event){ $(\u201c# mytext\u201d).css(\u201ctransform\u201d, \u201crotate(60)\u201d); }); </script> The above example rotates mytext by 90degrees using css and js rotates it again by 60 degrees. Not very cool but gives you an idea goodluck! ",
